1
00:00:05,000 --> 00:00:07,250
It's the middle of a keynote.

2
00:00:07,550 --> 00:00:09,800
The speaker's laptop has just died.

3
00:00:10,100 --> 00:00:12,350
Slides are frozen on the projector.

4
00:00:12,650 --> 00:00:14,650
The room is watching.

5
00:00:14,950 --> 00:00:17,575
Your AV engineer is on comms but

6
00:00:17,875 --> 00:00:20,125
everyone is talking at once and

7
00:00:20,425 --> 00:00:23,050
nobody's agreeing on what to try first.

8
00:00:23,350 --> 00:00:27,475
This is the situation that the Incident Advisor was built for.

9
00:00:27,775 --> 00:00:30,025
It's an AI-powered emergency co-pilot that

10
00:00:30,325 --> 00:00:32,575
lives inside CueDeck — and when

11
00:00:32,875 --> 00:00:36,625
things go sideways on stage, it gives you a diagnosis

12
00:00:36,925 --> 00:00:40,300
and a numbered action plan in under ten seconds.

13
00:00:40,600 --> 00:00:43,600
Let me show you exactly how it works.

14
00:00:43,900 --> 00:00:48,775
The Incident Advisor is one of three AI agent modules built into CueDeck.

15
00:00:49,075 --> 00:00:51,700
It lives in the AI Agents panel,

16
00:00:51,1000 --> 00:00:55,375
which is visible only to the Director role —

17
00:00:55,675 --> 00:00:59,425
because this is a tool for the person running the

18
00:00:59,725 --> 00:01:02,725
production, not for every operator on the floor.

19
00:01:03,025 --> 00:01:05,650
It's powered by Claude, Anthropic's AI model,

20
00:01:05,950 --> 00:01:08,200
running through a server-side proxy —

21
00:01:08,500 --> 00:01:12,625
so there's no API key to set up, no configuration required.

22
00:01:12,925 --> 00:01:15,925
The feature is included in all CueDeck plans,

23
00:01:16,225 --> 00:01:20,350
and it works the moment you're logged in as a director.

24
00:01:20,650 --> 00:01:23,650
You trigger it manually when something goes wrong.

25
00:01:23,950 --> 00:01:26,575
You describe the incident, it analyses it,

26
00:01:26,875 --> 00:01:29,875
and it comes back with a structured plan.

27
00:01:30,175 --> 00:01:34,300
To open it, click Incident Advisor in the AI Agents panel.

28
00:01:34,600 --> 00:01:37,225
You'll get this modal — dark background,

29
00:01:37,525 --> 00:01:40,900
red accent bar at the top, which is intentional.

30
00:01:41,200 --> 00:01:43,200
This isn't a settings panel.

31
00:01:43,500 --> 00:01:47,250
This is an emergency tool and it looks like one.

32
00:01:47,550 --> 00:01:50,550
At the top you'll see a title field,

33
00:01:50,850 --> 00:01:53,100
a metadata line showing location and

34
00:01:53,400 --> 00:01:56,400
timestamp, and below that the body area where

35
00:01:56,700 --> 00:01:58,700
the AI response will appear.

36
00:01:58,1000 --> 00:02:01,1000
The modal is already rendering a spinner —

37
00:02:02,300 --> 00:02:05,300
it's waiting for you to describe the incident.

38
00:02:05,600 --> 00:02:08,225
Here's where you describe what's actually happening.

39
00:02:08,525 --> 00:02:12,275
Be specific — the more context you give the AI,

40
00:02:12,575 --> 00:02:15,950
the more specific the action plan you'll get back.

41
00:02:16,250 --> 00:02:18,500
I'll type: speaker's laptop died mid-keynote,

42
00:02:18,800 --> 00:02:21,050
slides not loading on backup HDMI,

43
00:02:21,350 --> 00:02:24,350
three minutes in, room of four hundred waiting.

44
00:02:24,650 --> 00:02:29,150
One thing worth noting: the Incident Advisor knows about your current event.

45
00:02:29,450 --> 00:02:31,700
It has context — session title,

46
00:02:32,000 --> 00:02:35,000
the room, the planned timing, what's currently live.

47
00:02:35,300 --> 00:02:38,300
So your description doesn't need to repeat that.

48
00:02:38,600 --> 00:02:40,600
Just describe the problem.

49
00:02:40,900 --> 00:02:42,900
And here it comes.

50
00:02:43,200 --> 00:02:46,575
The spinner animates while Claude processes the incident —

51
00:02:46,875 --> 00:02:50,625
this takes under ten seconds on a normal connection —

52
00:02:50,925 --> 00:02:52,925
and then the response populates.

53
00:02:53,225 --> 00:02:55,475
First you get a Diagnosis block.

54
00:02:55,775 --> 00:03:00,275
This is the AI's interpretation of what is technically happening and why.

55
00:03:00,575 --> 00:03:04,325
For a laptop-and-HDMI failure, it might identify a signal handshake

56
00:03:04,625 --> 00:03:07,250
issue, a source-not-detected problem on the switcher,

57
00:03:07,550 --> 00:03:11,675
or a display timeout — based on the symptoms you described.

58
00:03:11,975 --> 00:03:13,975
Below that, Resolution Steps.

59
00:03:14,275 --> 00:03:16,525
These are numbered, ordered by priority,

60
00:03:16,825 --> 00:03:20,575
and they're interactive — you can click each one to

61
00:03:20,875 --> 00:03:24,250
mark it done as your crew works through them.

62
00:03:24,550 --> 00:03:27,925
The steps are specific: check the switcher output assignment,

63
00:03:28,225 --> 00:03:30,850
toggle EDID, pull and re-seat the HDMI,

64
00:03:31,150 --> 00:03:35,275
switch to the house laptop, advance manually from the operator station.

65
00:03:35,575 --> 00:03:39,325
And down in the footer — an estimated resolution time.

66
00:03:39,625 --> 00:03:43,375
The AI calculates this based on the severity of the

67
00:03:43,675 --> 00:03:45,925
issue and the steps it's recommending.

68
00:03:46,225 --> 00:03:48,475
In this case: approximately four minutes.

69
00:03:48,775 --> 00:03:51,400
As your crew works through the steps,

70
00:03:51,700 --> 00:03:53,700
you check them off.

71
00:03:54,000 --> 00:03:57,000
Each one turns green with a strikethrough —

72
00:03:57,300 --> 00:03:59,925
giving you a running view of where

73
00:04:00,225 --> 00:04:02,225
you are in the resolution.

74
00:04:02,525 --> 00:04:05,525
Your stage manager is on one comms channel,

75
00:04:05,825 --> 00:04:08,075
your AV lead is on another,

76
00:04:08,375 --> 00:04:12,125
and you're coordinating from this modal while the room waits.

77
00:04:12,425 --> 00:04:16,925
When the issue is resolved, hit Mark Resolved at the bottom right.

78
00:04:17,225 --> 00:04:20,600
CueDeck logs the incident to your event log —

79
00:04:20,900 --> 00:04:22,900
system, location, timestamp, resolved status.

80
00:04:23,200 --> 00:04:26,950
That entry will show up later in your post-event report.

81
00:04:27,250 --> 00:04:31,000
If the issue is beyond your team's ability to fix

82
00:04:31,300 --> 00:04:33,550
on-site, you have the Escalate button.

83
00:04:33,850 --> 00:04:37,600
That fires a notification through your configured escalation channel —

84
00:04:37,900 --> 00:04:41,275
and also logs the escalation to the event log.

85
00:04:41,575 --> 00:04:46,450
A few notes on when to reach for this versus when not to.

86
00:04:46,750 --> 00:04:49,000
The Incident Advisor is for unexpected,

87
00:04:49,300 --> 00:04:51,925
time-sensitive technical failures — laptop not connecting,

88
00:04:52,225 --> 00:04:54,850
PA system cutting out, streaming encoder dropping,

89
00:04:55,150 --> 00:04:57,150
interpretation channel going silent.

90
00:04:57,450 --> 00:05:00,825
Anything where you need a structured response fast and

91
00:05:01,125 --> 00:05:05,250
you don't have time to think through the full troubleshooting tree.

92
00:05:05,550 --> 00:05:08,175
It is not for planned schedule changes,

93
00:05:08,475 --> 00:05:10,475
late speakers, or administrative issues.

94
00:05:10,775 --> 00:05:13,775
Those go through the session state machine —

95
00:05:14,075 --> 00:05:16,325
delay nudge, hold, call speaker —

96
00:05:16,625 --> 00:05:18,625
not through the Incident Advisor.

97
00:05:18,925 --> 00:05:21,550
The best way to think of it:

98
00:05:21,850 --> 00:05:26,725
it's the equivalent of having a senior AV engineer looking over your shoulder.

99
00:05:27,025 --> 00:05:29,650
One who has seen every failure mode,

100
00:05:29,950 --> 00:05:32,575
doesn't panic, and gives you numbered steps.

101
00:05:32,875 --> 00:05:34,875
That's the Incident Advisor.

102
00:05:35,175 --> 00:05:38,550
One click, describe the problem, get a diagnosis and

103
00:05:38,850 --> 00:05:42,225
a ranked action plan in under ten seconds —

104
00:05:42,525 --> 00:05:44,775
while your event is still running.

105
00:05:45,075 --> 00:05:48,825
In the next episode we're covering the Cue Engine —

106
00:05:49,125 --> 00:05:51,125
the second AI agent module.

107
00:05:51,425 --> 00:05:55,175
That one fires eight minutes before every session start and

108
00:05:55,475 --> 00:05:59,225
runs through a readiness checklist so you never go live

109
00:05:59,525 --> 00:06:03,650
with a cold microphone or a slide deck that isn't loaded.

110
00:06:03,950 --> 00:06:05,950
I'll see you there.
